From fe4773673e7b679e66bb55634a8a561299f0ddba Mon Sep 17 00:00:00 2001
From: Matthew Feickert <matthew.feickert@cern.ch>
Date: Tue, 17 Feb 2026 23:05:00 -0700
Subject: [PATCH] fix: Ignore unknown arguments passed by conda/pip to setup.py

When rattler-build (and conda-build) run the build with VERBOSE=1, they
inject --verbose into the Python setup.py invocation. The custom
argparse-based setup.py has no --verbose argument, causing it to exit
with status 2:

  setup.py: error: unrecognized arguments: --verbose

The script already works around one such injected flag (--egg-base "does
nothing, for compatibility"), but rather than enumerate every flag that
build tooling may inject, switch from parse_args() to parse_known_args().

parse_known_args() returns a (namespace, extras) tuple and silently
discards any arguments it does not recognise, which is the correct
behaviour for a setup.py that only cares about its own defined flags.
---
 setup.py | 2 +-
 1 file changed, 1 insertion(+), 1 deletion(-)

diff --git a/setup.py b/setup.py
index cfb889bf..a03ab70c 100755
--- a/setup.py
+++ b/setup.py
@@ -348,7 +348,7 @@ def parse_args():
                        dest='spatial_solvers',
                        help='Do NOT build spatial solvers')
 
-    ns = parser.parse_args(argv)
+    ns, _ = parser.parse_known_args(argv)
     update_setup_args(ns)
     update_cmake_args(ns)
     update_make_args(ns)
